id: pm-m2il
title: "Graph conformance and scale verification matrix: property, replay, migration, concurrency, token-budget, and million-item tests"
description: "Build a reusable verification program for relationship schemas, immutable mutations, bounded queries, analytics, governance, adapters, and reconstruction waves."
type: Chore
status: in_progress
priority: 2
tags[7]: "area:graph",benchmark,conformance,property-testing,scale,testing,token-efficiency
created_at: "2026-07-13T22:03:31.210Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-14T10:19:37.624Z"
assignee: codex-gpt5
author: codex-root
estimated_minutes: 600
acceptance_criteria: "Fixtures cover empty and seconds-old scratch projects, representative medium histories, deep and cyclic typed graphs, multi-decade event streams, disconnected archives, and deterministic 10k, 100k, and one-million-item workspaces; Property tests cover registry invariants, inverse and alias rules, append-only mutation, replay equivalence, snapshot isolation, cursor stability, migration, merge or federation, and correction by superseding event; Algorithm tests verify exact results on bounded fixtures and deterministic seeds, error bounds, freshness, provenance, and monotonic resource limits for approximations; Concurrency tests exercise thousands-agent read and write contention, crashes, stale indexes, retries, idempotency, checkpoints, and non-overlapping reconstruction claims; CLI, MCP, SDK, extension, and shell pipeline parity share golden semantics while allowing intentionally different compact projections; Performance gates record p50, p95, and p99 latency, peak memory, incremental update cost, bytes and tokens, truncation quality, and index rebuild time with documented hardware and envelopes; Every test runs in sandboxed PM_PATH and PM_GLOBAL_PATH and never reads or writes the real repository tracker"
goal: Trustworthy typed graph context from tiny to million-item workspaces
objective: "Prove every graph capability and adapter against one adversarial, replayable, scale-aware conformance matrix"
value: Implementers get a stable completion gate and extensions can verify compatibility without duplicating fixtures
impact: "Catches semantic drift, nondeterminism, hidden full scans, replay failures, false cycles, concurrency races, and token regressions before release"
outcome: "Public test fixtures and helpers, property suites, golden projections, scale envelopes, adapter parity checks, and reconstruction-wave gates"
why_now: "The graph program spans SDK, CLI, MCP, packages, history, indexes, analytics, and audits, so acceptance criteria need one explicit cross-cutting verification owner"
parent: pm-96h7
risk: medium
confidence: high
